[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm wondering if there is a combinatorial proof of the surface classification theorem, presented in e.g. Munkres' Topology; that is, that every triangulated surface, represented by a \"labelling scheme\", can be normalized using a set of rewriting rules and shown to be equivalent one of the basic surface types.<br>\nThis feels like something that wouldn't be too hard to formalize, but I'm not sure how one would write down some of the necessary definitions.</p>",
        "id": 424372868,
        "sender_full_name": "Timothy Mou",
        "timestamp": 1709363670
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(deleted)</p>",
