    {
        "content": "<p>This would be a great project! I guess the hard part after that would be relating that combinatorial argument to a statement about topological spaces.</p>",
        "id": 424376651,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1709364905
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah that would be probably more involved. To be clear, it's been a while since I studied topology and I wouldn't know how to write that stuff. But what motivated this question was just musing over how to write some of the basic definitions. For instance, a \"labelling scheme\" is just a word like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">aba^{-1}b^{-1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ab</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> where each label <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span></span></span></span> can appear as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span></span></span></span> or \"reversed\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a^{-1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. A \"proper labelling scheme\" is a labelling scheme where each label appears exactly twice. Labelling schemes are also equivalent under cyclic rotation and some other rules.<br>\nSo we could represent a labelling scheme as just a list, how would we define a proper labelling scheme?</p>",
        "id": 424380368,
        "sender_full_name": "Timothy Mou",
        "timestamp": 1709365857
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Can't you use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=FreeGroup#doc\">docs#FreeGroup</a> for this?</p>",
        "id": 424406285,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1709381264
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>A \"proper labelling scheme\" is a labelling scheme where each label appears exactly twice.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For instance, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">aba^{-1}b^{-1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ab</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is valid, but <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">abaab^{-1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">abaa</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is not. I don't see how free groups would enforce that.</p>",
        "id": 424436969,
        "sender_full_name": "Timothy Mou",
        "timestamp": 1709406242
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Free groups would also not distinguish between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">aa^{-1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, although maybe that's one of the rules?</p>",
        "id": 424442339,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1709410367
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Apparently, the combinatorial classification of surfaces has been attempted by Dehlinger and <a href=\"https://dblp.org/pid/80/792.html\">Dufourd</a> in Coq:<br>\n<em><a href=\"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/3-540-45685-6_11\">Formalizing the Trading Theorem for the Classification of Surfaces</a></em> (paywalled)<br>\n<em><a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304397504003640\">Formalizing the trading theorem in Coq</a></em><br>\n<em><a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304397504003652\">Formalizing generalized maps in Coq</a></em><br>\n<em><a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S092577211400056X\">Formal specification and proofs for the topology and classification of combinatorial surfaces</a></em> (this paper was received in 2004 and published in 2014!)</p>\n<p>Here are two excerpts from the last paper:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/sy4c6r2SZf9WbVyC3QHPUIoY/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/U1ZFcOVkcT4rIX8LfEEPnHa7/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/sy4c6r2SZf9WbVyC3QHPUIoY/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/3121/sy4c6r2SZf9WbVyC3QHPUIoY/image.png\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/U1ZFcOVkcT4rIX8LfEEPnHa7/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/3121/U1ZFcOVkcT4rIX8LfEEPnHa7/image.png\"></a></div><p>Apparently, they divide the classification into the normalization theorem (the first part, Section 8) and the trading theorem (the second part, Section 7), and from the earlier papers it seems they successfully accomplished the second part, but apparently they're not claiming they proved the whole theorem. Here are the description of the two sub-theorems from the second paper:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/kcQ0hMzq3wK0jpm2aHo_gkJt/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/gHuEEF7FpNjZaYHG6_eOCnpP/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/w19teeohPrbymj6Szk_89vk2/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/kcQ0hMzq3wK0jpm2aHo_gkJt/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/3121/kcQ0hMzq3wK0jpm2aHo_gkJt/image.png\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/gHuEEF7FpNjZaYHG6_eOCnpP/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/3121/gHuEEF7FpNjZaYHG6_eOCnpP/image.png\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/w19teeohPrbymj6Szk_89vk2/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/3121/w19teeohPrbymj6Szk_89vk2/image.png\"></a></div><p>There's a <a href=\"http://dpt-info.u-strasbg.fr/~jfd/DD-CGTA13/ngold.tar.gz\">link</a> in the paper that is supposed to contain code, but it's dead now probably because J.-F. Dufourd has retired ...</p>\n<p>They give five references other than the main reference (Griffiths' <em>Surfaces</em>, 1981), but Munkres isn't among them, so I'm not sure how well the argument translates (note that they work with open surfaces rather than closed). But they do say \"the approach that we follow in this section is common to most textbooks on surfaces [35,23,43,28,25]\".</p>\n<p>Overall, I'd expect the combinatorial classification of surfaces to be easier than the combinatorial part of <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"266253\">@Joseph Myers</span>'s proposed aperiodic monotile formalization.</p>\n<p>See also some earlier <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Daniel.20Busch/near/261525866\">discussion on Zulip</a> in 2021.</p>",
        "id": 424446398,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1709414232
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Silvia De Toffoli talks specifically about the role which diagrams play in the classification of surfaces in her 2023 paper <a href=\"https://journals.publishing.umich.edu/phimp/article/id/1348/\">here</a>, on the role of diagrams in mathematics. She points out that \"removing the diagrams from the proof\" (e.g. writing a diagram-free proof of the result in a textbook) would have epistemic and cognitive disadvantages. Formalisation perhaps solves the epistemic disadvantages; perhaps a more advanced theory of widgets would fix up the cognitive ones?</p>",
        "id": 424663889,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1709561523
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> As it happens, I'm working on a Lean-compatible method of checking/generating diagrammatic proofs at the moment. Though it remains to be seen how long it'll take me... &gt;.&gt;;</p>\n<p>(The primary use case is Penrose diagrammatic notation and tensor calculus, but on general principle I'm designing it to be compatible with any calculus that can be represented by a braided monoidal category, i.e. most string diagrams that don't assign data to the space between strings, though I'm leaving it open in case I do hit on a good way to represent such cases without massively adding to the technical scope of the project.)</p>",
        "id": 426243353,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1710294640
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"359992\">@Robert Maxton</span>, you know about <a href=\"http://homotopy.io\">homotopy.io</a>, right?</p>",
        "id": 426244110,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1710295046
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110087\">Scott Morrison</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/.28combinatorial.29.20surface.20classification.20theorem/near/426244110\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"359992\">Robert Maxton</span>, you know about <a href=\"http://homotopy.io\">homotopy.io</a>, right?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Nope, and thank you for the reference, it'll be very helpful when writing my other proofs!</p>\n<p><del>However, when I play with it, I note quite quickly that it is very good at the thing it is designed for, and cannot be easily generalized to do other things, like, say, vector/tensor calculus. (At the least, the existing tensor calculus notation does not translate into string diagrams of this sort well; there probably is a way to create a new graphical calculus that does, but to some extent that would rather defeat the purpose.)</del> </p>\n<p>So I will have to continue with my original program... though I might borrow some ideas regarding implementing n-cells.</p>",
        "id": 426250022,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1710298530
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>.... Hm. I take that back, I just didn't know how to use it right, I think. I'll have to play with it more.</p>",
        "id": 426252590,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1710300165
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Certainly all \"Penrose\" diagrams, calculus for monoidal/braided categories can be done in <a href=\"http://homotopy.io\">homotopy.io</a>.</p>",
        "id": 426253063,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1710300567
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The big thing they are lacking is a way of saying \"a functor consists of &lt;a list of cells&gt;\", \"a natural transformation consists of ...\" and then to be able to say in a different file \"let s be a natural transformation from F to G\".</p>",
        "id": 426253145,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1710300624
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah I tried to build a 3-cell in the way most obvious to me, saw that it didn't work, and assumed it was something fundamental ^.^;. But then I read the actual paper and saw they'd basically done Penrose in the appendix, so now I'm trying to figure out how to do that myself</p>",
        "id": 426253186,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1710300675
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Mm. Actually, upon playing with the model a bit more, I think I'm reverting to my original position, though now with a somewhat stronger basis lol</p>",
        "id": 426296155,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1710323301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>even setting up a ring structure is somewhat annoying, and the lack of an automatical 'dual' that isn't 'inverse' (in general, the fact that it has distinguished directions) makes it not ideal for a number of use cases<br>\nagain, it's great for homotopy, and it's certainly <em>possible</em> to set it up for most of Penrose, but... <br>\nalso, I don't see a great way of extending it to include e.g. derivatives</p>",
        "id": 426296445,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1710323411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could you say more about the type of diagrammatic proofs you're thinking about. I'm not sure how derivatives come in.</p>",
        "id": 426313926,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1710328954
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, for example, Maxwell's homogenous equations <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∂</mi><mi>α</mi></msub><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><msup><mi>η</mi><mrow><mi>α</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi>η</mi><mrow><mi>β</mi><mi>δ</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∂</mi><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>γ</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>A</mi><mrow><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow></msub><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>J</mi><mi>β</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\partial_\\alpha \\left(\\eta^{\\alpha\\gamma}\\eta^{\\beta\\delta}\\partial_{[\\gamma}A_{\\delta]}\\right) = J^{\\beta}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2052em;vertical-align:-0.3552em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">∂</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0556em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">η</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">η</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">δ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">∂</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198em;margin-left:-0.0556em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3552em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198e